The new Python harness has undeclared dependencies that will break clean dev/test installs, and its dense baseline does not match the engine's current default pooling mode. These issues can invalidate CI and the reported baseline numbers.

Full review comments:

- [P1] Declare the new Python dependencies — /home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb/src/python/eval/m1_baseline.py:60-60
  In a clean environment following `pip install -e 'src/python[dev]'`, `numpy` is not installed because `src/python/pyproject.toml` still has no runtime/dev/test dependency for it. These new modules and tests import `numpy` at collection time, so the Python test/typecheck loop fails with `ModuleNotFoundError` before any harness gating can run.

- [P2] Match the engine pooling mode for dense baselines — /home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb/src/python/eval/m1_baseline.py:341-342
  When the reported `passage_dense`/`fused` arms are meant to represent the engine's pinned default embedder, this uses the `[CLS]` vector, but the current Rust `CandleBgeEmbedder::new()` default is `Pooling::Mean`. That means every dense ranking and fused comparator artifact from this harness is produced in a different embedding space than FathomDB's default embedder, invalidating the claimed baseline comparison unless the engine is also switched to CLS for this run.
